text: What do you have to say about Slavic culture in other cultures? We are the last generation who in 1952 visited Germany. I don't know what it is exactly, it must be... Yeah, somewhere it's written. Who helped the North? And we were the last family to be sent to America. I remember that because we have photos and articles of how my parents were so lucky to have been sent to America. And I think we were the last family, because we had to come earlier, I had written my name and was told that we were coming to America, my grandmother came a year earlier, but then my mother took the child and my brother was born in November just before that, and I think the truth was that it was true. And since we were the last family, then slowly there was the Hungarian Revolution and Hungary began to bring those refugees, then we were invited to New York, and I remember it so well, I was seven or eight, we stood there with the American flyers and we greeted them, and it was very exciting to me, because so young, the first time I was in a hotel somewhere, and we talked very politely, we did interviews and so on. I think since we were the last, we came to Flying Tiger Airlines, and I know that we flew over Irima, and we had to stay in Irima, because there was something with the plane, I don't know if it was a propeller or something, it was a problem, but then again we got better, and I think we were there for a very long time, maybe above or something, and then we flew to New York, so we didn't have the same number of flights, and then we took our bags with us to Seabrook. Seabrook is a small village in Luna, New Jersey, and it's probably about three hours, four hours by bus from New York. And Seabrook, because there was one work there, which was called Seabrook Farms, Charles F. Seabrook, was more than 30-40 years old, he built a big house for himself, and a cooling factory there, and it was one of America's first deep cooling factories, with a deep cooling of the soil and wood. And he needed a job, and he really needed a job in the summer, when it was just the right time, when everything was growing, before the Estonians came there, the Japanese came there, and the Japanese, because when America was at war with Japan, the Japanese were also sent to the concentration camps, because the Japanese who lived in America, when there were riots in America, they started to fight there, or they started to fight, but more likely, you know, to associate with Japan and do some kind of great work, or I don't know what they thought. They were the Japanese who were living there, they had their own homes, their own houses, and it was like sending, not only, you know, like sending a message to Russia. Every time they were sent to the camp, they were told, take what you can carry with you, they had been in the camp for a few years, and then when the war ended, then the children, you know, what they were looking for now, and of course their homes and places where they had already been, they couldn't go back there, they had to be evacuated or sold, maybe some of them were left alone, but most of them had to start a new life, so they also came to Cyprus, because Cyprus gave them work and life. In the middle of the 50s, there were maybe six hundred people, six hundred Estonians. In my opinion, I have read somewhere, that at least a thousand Estonians ever moved through there. Some people came there, only for a couple of months they moved on, maybe they got in touch with some of my relatives, or some better work, but we lived there, I lived there for two years. I think that's why my father had a good place to live there. When people came there, they were given a place to live, there was furniture, there was food, there was laundry, all sorts of things. There were benches, where they could buy food, where they needed it. There was clothing there. And my friends were there, when I grew up, Japanese and Estonians. And we were there in school, like beggars, we were always in the first classes. We had a tough life in Estonia. There was an Estonian Sunday school, which was held on Sundays, but there was also a writing component, but also Estonian, a little bit of practice, singing in Estonian, rafting, Estonian culture. And Estonian books, bags in Estonia, that was a big part of my life, to get bags in Estonia. I remember how they gathered measurements, what to get, if it was possible to get some extra bags. Then, of course, the bags from which I grew up, which were always in a good condition, especially since it was me, and I had three brothers. These two brothers were born in Zibruk. They opened a coffee shop, certainly, I don't know what else went there. They planned for a long time how to get the bag in, and then finally the packing, making, and then a list of things around it, so that it would be certain, and then on the address. I don't know if I had to go to Philadelphia, or I think I had to go somewhere far away from where to get it, where to get the bag in Europe or in Estonia. When I was five months old, even 54-55, I started to go back. I remember that my grandfather, my grandfather Herman Merican, who still lived in Tartu, had changed his name a little. He was not a Merican, he was a Merican. Don't forget that he was my grandfather's great-grandfather, who was a police officer. And the letters always went around, so that in the beginning, that letter was not even for my grandfather. You know, it somehow meant that you didn't have to name who you were writing to, because there was also the feeling that you didn't want to hurt people who live in Estonia, someone who has been arrested and who may have been a German soldier or a policeman or whatever, that it is now in contact with them. I remember the letters that my mother and grandmother sent me, what was going on there and what was going on there. And they reminded me of Estonia all the time. And what always made me laugh was that my grandmother always had different memories. It was on that day. No, it wasn't on that day, it was on that day. What do you know? Do you know anything? No, I don't know very well, I know some things. The thing I grew up with, and my mother was like, oh, she was such a great communist, Russian, red-skinned, and we were not red-skinned either. That was for sure. And everything in the world that was red-skinned, communist, Russian, that was also for sure. But my mother was like, this is the thing, I have heard so much about it, that her parents were killed. Her parents were killed very quickly, very quickly. One uncle was killed by a knife in Siberia. The other one, who was killed by a knife, he had three children, one was a boy, and that boy was killed by a gun, and that boy was killed by a knife. When you grow up, I remember friends with whom you grow up, who are not Estonians, Americans, they have old mothers, they have old fathers, they have fathers, they have great-grandfathers, they have grandparents, you read children's stories, we didn't have old things, we had only the things that we had when we came. We didn't have old memories of that country. All our things were in Estonia, our memories, our burnings, our old things, our relatives. There was a fire in Estonia, a house fire, for one person who had never been there, but it was a house fire. You get off the ship and then you see that you have been on the back of the wheel, and you are on this side, and you can see through it, you are on the back of the wheel, and I immediately walked there, and everyone was standing on the side, and I felt them all. I didn't see them in my life, but I was raised with letters, like my mother and grandfather, and I stood there, and there were Livi, Elmo, Kai, Mati, and there were a lot of people who I didn't see in my life, but they were your own people.
